Restoring the very American ideal that labor rights are also human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a bill to protect union organizing as a civil right.
"The way unions work, middle-class jobs work," said Ellison, a Democratic senator from Minnesota who is co-chair of a congressional committee.
That is why I am so proud to introduce a law empowering employees, along with John Lewis, a model of occasional rights.
This groundbreaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to prevent discrimination in unionisation as in other forms of discrimination – and stop anti-union forces
Amending the Labour Relations Act to allow all employees who face discrimination if they want to join a trade union to sue in a civil court - and to seek compensation or damages - is a right and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and the other sponsors are proposing in the bill is to rebuild the American ideal.
Despite union struggles in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states — Americans once supported countries around the world to adopt, expand, and respect labor rights.
There was a time, and millions of Americans still remember, when the country championed democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to assemble in the same breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers encouraged the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the military autocracy of Hideki Toya was replaced by democracy.
Convinced that workers and their unions had a role to play in shaping the new Japan, they incorporated language into them and openly acknowledged that "the right of workers to assemble, bargain collectively, and negotiate is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers urged the Germans to create a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
The Germans, realizing that the workers would need to organize and assert themselves in the new nation, included a clause that openly stated: "The right to form associations that will secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and to every profession or profession.
Arrangements that restrict this right or seek to infringe it will be repealed. Measures to fulfil such a purpose are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations as a global treaty in 1948, the proponents and Roosevelt included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to form and join trade unions for the protection of his interests."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create a civil and democratic society, Americans explained that the right to form labor unions—and their participation in collective bargaining with firms and government agencies as equal partners—must be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is imperative to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and assert themselves in a free and open society.
As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today everyone knows that the unions did not diminish the strength of the nation, but expanded it.
They raised the standard of living of millions of people, created a market for industry and raised production to an unprecedented level.
Those who attack the unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History does not forget, and neither should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of civil rights protections to prevent discrimination in trade union organisation - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis restore the ideals that lifted America and made it a true promise of democracy.
A judge temporarily blocked a law that could have closed all abortion clinics in Louisiana
A federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked a Louisiana law that advocates say would likely close all five abortion clinics in the state.
The order, enacted by Louisiana Gov. Bobby Jindal's signature in June, which is set to take effect on Sept. 1, would require abortion doctors to have the right to admit a patient to a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
The judge's order means that doctors can temporarily continue to perform legal abortions and must obtain that permission in the meantime.
"The petitioning party will be able to lawfully conduct its business and in the meantime obtain a permit," federal Judge John deGravelles said in a ruling.
The hearing will be scheduled within a month to allow the judge to issue a more permanent order on the law.
Abortion rights activists welcomed the resolution, the latest in a series of similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain permission.
"Today's decision assures women in Louisiana that they will be safe from a sneaky bill designed to deprive them of their health and rights," said Nancy Northup, president and executive director of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who sued on behalf of three of the five clinics to block the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision also applied to doctors from two clinics that were not among the plaintiffs and were also applying for permission.
Louisiana is among eleven states that have passed similar laws, with courts in Alabama and Mississippi declaring such measures unconstitutional.
Key parts of the Texas law that would have closed most of the state's remaining clinics were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Women's abortion rights campaigners, along with the Association of Obstetricians and Gynecologists of America and the American Medical Association, argue that requiring such a permit places medically unnecessary requirements on physicians.
Abortion opponents countered that the measures were intended to protect women's health, and some welcomed the fact that the measures would close clinics.
The Center for Reproductive Rights said only one abortion doctor in Louisiana is authorized.
If all doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, that doctor would also stop performing the procedure out of fear for his safety, the group said.
In response, Louisiana authorities said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while they wait for a rights application to be processed.
