Women in rural Australia are at a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than their urban counterparts.
Researchers analysed the medical records of more than 1100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005 and found that only 35% lived five years after diagnosis.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Medical Research Institute said women in rural and remote areas of the state were about twenty percent more likely to die during the study than women in urban areas.
