Women in rural and remote areas of the state were about twenty percent more likely to die during the study than women in urban areas.
Although the study wasn't designed to determine why women living outside the city were more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan says late diagnosis and poor access to treatment may be factors.
