Israeli children return to school after Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children from areas near the Gaza Strip returned to school on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters while rockets and mortars attacked their homes during the fifty-day war between Israel and Hamas. But schools in Gaza remain closed as the territory recovers from the fighting.
The start of school has brought a sense of joy and excitement to communities in southern Israel scarred by the attacks, but signs of fighting are still visible.
In Ashdod, a city in the south of the country, employees of a kindergarten hit by a rocket have removed shrapnel from a wall and are slowly awaiting the return of the children.
"We're a little scared, but otherwise we're looking forward to it," said Ronit Bart, a resident of Kibbutz Saad and an English teacher at a local school.
A lot of kids in this area really need to get back to their daily routine.
Her eleven-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said it was "a bit strange" to suddenly go back to school.
"We had a couple of tough times and didn't leave the house at all," she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited the kibbutz, which is close to the Gaza border, to offer his support to the population.
Until a ceasefire last week ended the war, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad remained inside their homes or left their homes for safer areas further from Gaza to escape rockets and mortars.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a village near the Gaza border where a Palestinian mortar shell killed a four-year-old boy, are hesitant to return.
The education minister said about a dozen families had still not returned.
Their children were temporarily placed in foster schools.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the Gaza border that has been hit hard by Palestinian fire.
He urged children to study hard, adding, "We will provide you with education and safety."
Israel and Hamas agreed last Tuesday to an indefinite peace.
While the ceasefire led to an immediate cessation of hostilities, it did not resolve key issues such as Hamas's demand to end the Israeli-Egyptian blockade of Gaza and reopen Gaza's airports and ports.
Israel is demanding the disarmament of Hamas and the return of the bodies of two soldiers killed in the war.
A new round of indirect negotiations is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
According to Palestinian and UN estimates, more than 2,100 Palestinians died in the war, three-quarters of whom were civilians and at least 494 children.
Israel disputes these figures, estimating that at least half of those killed were radicals, although it has no clear evidence for these claims.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians, including a Thai worker, died.
Hamas and other militants from Gaza fired 4,591 rockets and mortars at Israeli cities, mainly in the south of the country, during the fighting.
The Israeli military, for its part, has carried out more than 5,000 airstrikes and other attacks.
Israeli strikes have damaged or destroyed thousands of homes in Gaza, and an estimated 250,000 people have taken refuge in a hundred UN schools, which have been turned into makeshift shelters.
With tens of thousands of people still in hiding and ongoing fighting, school officials postponed the start of the school year last week.
"I hope they will open the school soon so that we can complete our education just like Jewish children and other children in the world," said Mohammad Amara, a thirteen-year-old boy from a school in Gaza's largest city.
