According to closely watched statistics, apartment prices in winter have risen the most in the last seven years.
According to the RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic index of apartment values in Australia, housing prices rose 1.1% in August, the agency said on Monday.
The increase led to an overall increase for June, July and August to 4.2%, the highest increase in the winter months since 2007.
Annual price increases climbed to 10.9%, more than double in the one year to August 2013, but profits were not evenly distributed across the country.
RP Data's research director Tim Lawless said Sydney and Melbourne lead the market.
RP Data figures show that Sydney apartment prices rose by 16.1% last year, while prices in Melbourne rose by 11.7%.
The next strongest markets were Adelaide, Brisbane and Darwin, with price increases averaging between five and six percent.
At the other end of the scale was Canberra, which has been hurt by state-mandated spending cuts and where prices rose by only 1.4% during the year.
Lawless said that now that spring has begun, the number of properties for sale will increase in the coming months, which will be a "real test" for the market.
"Given the persistently high auction sell-off rate, the generally high rate of sales and the low interest rate, housing values are likely to increase further over the next three months," he said.
