After two weeks of protests in Ferguson, Missouri, over the shooting of unarmed teenager Michael Brown, blogger Miriam Zoila Perez has noticed a shift in the online discussions of white feminists.
She found that when it comes to promoting reproductive rights and income equality, white feminists favor gender over race.
With tensions rising in the Midwest that attracted the attention of the national press, Perez noticed that white women's reaction was 100 percent race-centered.
Compared to the reactions of black women soon after the August 9 shooting, personal articles with headlines such as "White woman's reflections on Ferguson" and "Feminism is not just about oppressing women" appeared relatively late.
But according to Perez, this represents an important change.
"I don't think there are many people in the feminist movement who talk about race and privilege at that level," she said.
People felt they had to comment on what had happened.
It's characteristic of the crisis we're facing, because [the situation in Ferguson] is so racially charged that they had to point it out.
According to Koritha Mitchell, a professor of English at Ohio State University, Ferguson brought to light issues that African-American women face every day that are not seen as "women's issues" in the cultural sphere.
"I can post funny stories about life with my partner on Facebook and it gets 150 likes from people all over the world," Mitchell said.
When I write something about non-whites being trapped in their own country, the silence is deafening.
"How is it possible that a woman can speak publicly about relationships, but not about safety in public spaces?" she asked.
For black women like Mitchell, who have dealt with issues of race, gender, and sexuality in American history, there is no dichotomy between race and gender.
Black women, she said, didn't have the luxury of dividing up these problems: they live in this mixed reality every day.
Although white women now merge the issue of race and gender in mainstream feminist circles, Angela Hattery, a professor in women's question and gender studies at George Mason University, says their predecessors did the opposite.
Between 1865 and 1890, at least 10,000 black men were lynched, and almost all of them were caused by the rape of a white woman," Hattery said.
To justify the lynching, you needed the cooperation of white women.
According to Hattery, the split between white and black women came when women suffrage campaigners like Susan B. Anthony explored the terrain in the late 19th century and realized that only one group of people — women or blacks — could have the right to vote.
"They decided to bet their cards on women's voting rights and the right for blacks to focus later," Hattery explained.
Realizing this gives us an important insight into why women of color don't trust white women.
We did not do a good job.
We have never helped black women protect their husbands and children.
Even after women gained the right to vote in 1920, it took a decade before they began to organize against lynching in the Association of Southern Women for the Prevention of Lynching.
The group was formed 40 years after black women first asked for help.
According to Mitchell, the surge in white feminist reactions to the issues raised by Ferguson — police behavior, racial discrimination — reflects a time when white feminists had to "catch up" with issues that black women had grappled with for generations.
"Wouldn't it be great if activists in these spaces [of traditional feminism] took the right to raise a child as seriously as they took the right to contraception?"
A second wave of feminists who have made a career fighting for reproductive rights and access to contraception are now discovering what that means.
Two weeks after the shooting of Michael Brown, prominent feminist activists such as Gloria Steinem stormed Facebook, posting a column by the Guardian's Rebecca Carroll calling for white Americans to protest racism more forcefully.
"I hope that women who have different yet similar reasons for understanding the dangers in society — and views about race that differ widely in opinion polls — will push for change," Steinem wrote.
Although Steinem advocates an intersectional feminism that encompasses issues of both race and gender, her comments on race in America confuse some.
Christina Sommers, an expert at the American Enterprise Institute, author of "Who Stole Feminism?," told She The People that young men in the United States, especially young men of color, are "much more vulnerable than their sisters," but Steinem's comments about Ferguson have faced criticism she has previously sparked.
We now have hundreds of special programs for girls and young women, but almost none for boys.
But when the White House launched a small My Brother's Keeper program to help vulnerable young black men and Hispanics, it sparked angry reactions from many feminists, including Gloria Steinem.
The relationship of the police to the black community is not the only issue that has come to the forefront of mainstream feminism.
