Why the universe can have multiple dimensions and we can't see them
Physicists don't usually write bestsellers, but Brian Green of Columbia University did a hit in 1999.
His book The Elegant Universe has become the most accessible way for laymen to get into the thicket of problems that many theoretical physicists are engaged in today - the attempt to unify two well-functioning but mutually incompatible discoveries of the 20th century: quantum theory and the theory of general relativity.
One of the reasons for the success of The Elegant Universe is undoubtedly that the search for a unified physical theory is not a boring story.
Physicists have solved the basic problem between two key theories (after all, at this moment our universe is de facto divided into two worlds with different laws) and solve it so imaginatively that it is worth retelling even to laymen.
Moreover, Greene handled the complex material so freshly and engagingly that he cannot be blamed for not including anything interesting in his book.
Moreover, he largely corrected his "mistake" in two other books: The Structure of the Universe and The Hidden Reality.
Probably even the author would not object to his book becoming obsolete faster, but the fact is that even after 15 years, The Elegant Universe still provides almost everything essential that an informed layman with the ambition to understand the world should know about this important part of theoretical physics.
It is quite likely that in the coming years it will be a little livelier in this area (for example, due to the fact that the LHC accelerator will finally run at "full throttle"), so it is a good time to enter the door of the world of modern physics that is open by Green.
How many dimensions can our universe have?
The idea that our universe may have more than three spatial dimensions may sound silly, fantastic, strange, or mystical.
Nevertheless, it is concrete and completely acceptable.
To understand this, let's turn our gaze away from the universe as a whole for a moment to something more mundane, namely a long and thin garden watering hose.
Imagine stretching a hundred-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and watching the whole scenery from a distance of half a kilometer (as in the picture and on the next page).
From such a distance, you can easily spot a long, horizontally stretched hose, but unless you have an acumen of vision, you can hardly tell the thickness of the hose.
Given its great distance from the hose, you would think that an ant forced to live on a hose has only one dimension in which to walk: the left-right dimension along the hose.
When someone asks you where the ant was at any given moment, you answer with only one indication: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we want to say is that from half a kilometer away, a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, the hose has thickness.
If we enlarge everything, we suddenly see a second dimension - in the shape of a circle wrapping around a hose.
In such an enlarged view, it is clear that the ant can actually move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the "clockwise / counterclockwise dimension", i.e. around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You begin to understand that to determine the location of a small ant, you need to enter two numbers: how far it is from the end of the hose and where it is on the circle wrapping the hose.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional.
Non-perturbative aspects are discussed in chapters 12 and 13.).
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long longitudinal dimension is represented by a straight arrow, the dimension in the direction of the circumference, indicated by a circular arrow, is short and coiled.
However, there is a clear difference between the two dimensions.
The dimension along the hose is long and easy to see.
The dimension wrapping around the hose circumference is short, "coiled" and less noticeable.
To realize the existence of a circular dimension, we had to examine the hose with significantly better resolution.
This example illustrates an important property of spatial dimensions.
That they are divided into two groups.
They can be either large, sprawling, and therefore directly visible, or, on the contrary, small, coiled and much harder to observe.
Of course, in this case, we didn't exactly work hard to reveal the "coiled" dimension wrapping around the thickness of the hose.
It was enough to take binoculars to help.
But if the hose were thinner - like a hair or a capillary - we would only discover the coiled dimension with great effort.
Kaluza sent Einstein a paper in 1919 in which he came up with the astounding idea that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than three dimensions known to all of us.
Kaluza justified his radical claim by arguing that the additional dimension provides an elegant and convincing framework within which Einstein's general relativity and Maxwell's electromagnetic theory can be woven into a single, unified conceptual structure.
The question immediately arises as to how this observation of Kaluza fits in with the obvious fact that we see exactly three dimensions of space.
The answer that Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines, and which was clearly articulated and specified by the Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands or falls with the claim that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and coiled dimensions.
This means that, like the dimension in the direction of the length of the hose, our universe has three, large, and easily visible three dimensions whose existence we are aware of every moment.
But by analogy with the circular circumference of a garden hose, the universe can also have additional dimensions, tightly coiled into a space so tiny that they have hitherto remained hidden from even our most sophisticated experimental apparatus.
To get a clearer idea of the essence of Kaluza's remarkable design, let's dwell on the hose for a moment.
Imagine that on the perimeter of the hose we draw a fairly dense row of circles in black paint.
From a distance, the hose still looks like a thin one-dimensional line.
With binoculars, thanks to the drawing, we can now reveal the coiled dimension even more easily, because we can see the motif from Figure 2.
We can clearly see that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional, with one dimension large and almost limitless, and with the other short and circular.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that our universe has a similar structure, but apart from one small circular dimension, it has three large spatial dimensions, making a total of four spatial dimensions.
It is difficult to draw an object with too many dimensions.
To help our imagination a little, consider the illustration in Fig. 3; It shows two large dimensions and one small circular dimension.
In the picture, we magnify the view of the geometry of the space in a similar way as we enlarged the surface area of the hose.
Each subsequent level represents a huge increase in the geometry of space from the previous level.
Our universe can have additional dimensions (we see them at the fourth magnification level) if they are coiled into a small enough space; This explains why we have not yet directly observed them.
The square grid represents the commonly known "large" dimensions, while the circle represents the new, tiny, and coiled dimension.
Just like loops of thread in a densely woven carpet, these circles exist in every place of the usual dimensions - we just drew them for clarity only in the intersections in a square grid.
The background of Figure 4 shows the commonly known structure of space - the ordinary world around us - on such common scales as meters, represented by the side of a small square in a square grid.
In each of the following figures, we will focus on a small area of the previous image; We enlarge it so that it becomes visible.
Nothing special happens at first, as we see in the first few levels of magnification.
But when we go further on our journey to the microscopic properties of the geometry of space - to the fourth level of magnification in Figure 3 - we suddenly see a new, circle-shaped dimension, like the loops of thread in a densely woven piece of carpet.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that an additional circular dimension exists at every point in the direction of large dimensions, just as a hose has a circular circumference at every point of its length.
For the sake of clarity, we have drawn the circular dimension only in some, regularly spaced points.
Figure 4 summarizes Kaluza's and Klein's idea of the microscopic structure of the geometry of space.
The similarity with the hose is obvious, although we also note important differences.
First, the universe has three large, far-reaching spatial dimensions (of which we have drawn only two), while the hose has a large dimension of only one.
An even more important difference is that we are now talking about the spatial geometry of the universe itself, not just an object inside the universe, like our hose.
But the basic idea is the same.
If the additional circularly coiled dimension is extremely miniature, it is - like the circular circumference of the hose - much harder to recognize than to observe the obvious, large and extensive dimensions.
If the size of the additional dimension is small enough, it will actually reveal it beyond the power of our state-of-the-art magnification tools.
Most importantly, the additional dimension is not just a rounded bump within ordinary dimensions, as the two-dimensional illustration mistakenly suggests.
The circular dimension is a new dimension that exists at every point of the three common sprawling dimensions.
It is a dimension independent of the other three dimensions, just as the top-down, left-right, and front-to-back dimensions are independent (and perpendicular) of each other.
A sufficiently small ant could move in all four dimensions, and to determine its position we would need four data, in addition to the three usual positions in the circular dimension; If we count the time, then five data, in any case one more than we would normally expect.
