Putin asks Kiev to start negotiations on "state sovereignty" with eastern Ukraine
According to a description of the events by a Russian newspaper, Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded on Sunday that the Ukrainian government stop fighting with separatists in the east of the country and immediately begin negotiations on the "state sovereignty" of the breakaway regions.
His spokesman Dmitry Peskov later explained that Putin's remark was not meant to imply that the separatist-controlled areas of eastern Ukraine would become part of Russia, but that their status within Ukraine should be reassessed to give the Russian-speaking area the authority to protect its rights and interests.
Putin's call for the Kiev government to treat the pro-Russian rebels as equals corresponds to the apparent strategy it has followed since the riots erupted five months ago: Help the separatists seize territory and force the Ukrainian government to grant the newly declared Novorossiya de facto independence so that it can ally itself with Russia instead of the West.
In an interview with the first channel of state television, Putin condemned Ukrainian military actions aimed at retaking the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were seized by separatists in March and April after Moscow annexed Ukraine's Crimean peninsula on March 18.
The Kremlin and separatists have referred to the recently occupied territory as "Novorossiya" or "New Russia," a term that refers to the glorious pre-revolutionary days of the Russian Empire.
Russia's Itar-Tass news agency published Putin's words saying that a "prisoner of illusions" is anyone who believes peace talks are on the horizon because Ukrainian politicians have launched campaigns ahead of parliamentary elections on October 26, while government troops are attacking civilians in separatist-controlled areas.
"In the interest of the people living in these areas, we must immediately start meaningful negotiations, not only on legal matters, but also on the political organization of society and the status of state sovereignty of south-east Ukraine," he said.
Peskov said Putin's allusion to state sovereignty was meant in the context of broader autonomy, which has been under discussion with Kiev's leadership for months to allay concerns about Russian-speaking areas about threats to cultural and linguistic rights.
Peskov said that only the Ukrainian government could grant the necessary autonomy to the eastern regions.
This is not a matter to be discussed between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, "because it is not a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but an internal Ukrainian conflict."
The Kremlin spokesman's move to correct a "misinterpretation" of Putin's remarks underscored Russia's leadership's approach to dealing with the separatist insurgency in the east, which is different from the open occupation of Crimea, where most of the population of two million is ethnic Russian.
Moscow would also have much more difficulty annexing Donetsk and Luhansk in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million people are not Russians and opinion polls conducted before the conflict showed broad support for remaining in Ukraine.
The autonomy discussed by Russian diplomats in international forums would give regional governments in Ukraine the power to determine their own trade agreements and international relations, effectively giving the Kremlin de facto control over the territory that would connect the Russian mainland to Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, annexed five months ago, is home to Russia's main naval fleet, naval trading facilities and historic coastal resorts.
The areas between Russia's Rostov and Crimea are also the center of mines, factories and foundries that produce important components for the Russian military.
During his inauguration speech on June 7, Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko suggested that Ukrainian lawmakers — after new elections — consider changes to the constitution that would give diverse regions more control over their finances and language status.
But this vision of autonomy is very different from that of the Kremlin and the separatists. Moscow is accused of arming and inciting violence.
Putin's latest call for Kiev to treat the separatists as equals followed another rebel advance last week after Russian troops and tanks from a previously peaceful area along the Sea of Azov entered eastern Ukraine.
The separatists, reinforced by the Russians, have taken control of Novoazovsk with such force that Ukrainian security authorities fear it is a campaign to seize strategic coastal territory all the way to Crimea.
This precipitated a huge civilian and military effort to fortify Mariupol, a metallurgical port of 500,000 inhabitants that lies between Novoazovsk and the narrow gateway to the Crimean peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at a meeting of European Union leaders in Brussels on Saturday, urging action to prevent further Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for the past 23 years.
"We are approaching the point of no return," Poroshenko warned.
There are now thousands of foreign military units and hundreds of foreign tanks on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit did not take any definitive steps - leaders call for the adoption of further sanctions against Russia in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukrainian crisis.
Colonel Andriy Lysenko, a spokesman for Ukraine's National Security and Defense Council, told reporters in Kiev on Saturday that Ukrainian troops had to withdraw from their positions in Ilovaisk after two columns of Russian armored vehicles and 1,000 military units entered the Donetsk region last week to support besieged separatists.
The first of the 63 reported Ukrainian soldiers captured in Ilovaisk in the Russian invasion were exchanged on Sunday for 10 Russian paratroopers captured a week ago in the interior of Ukraine, Lysenko said on Sunday.
